		<header>
			
			<h1>ESA: Clock ticking for Kenyaâ€™s sugar industry under regional market opening </h1>

			
			<h4>
												03 February 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Press reports have raised concerns over the future of Kenyaâ€™s sugar sector in the context of the phasing out of the special safeguard provisions under the COMESA agreement in February 2012. According to press reports, the current â€˜four-year extension period â€¦ is the last Kenya is allowed to have under â€¦ the COMESA treatyâ€™. Kenya currently imports â€˜260,000 tonnes of sugar, approximately 36 per cent of the countryâ€™s consumption of 720,000 tonnes, from COMESA member countriesâ€™. It is argued that the Kenyan sugar industry has not to date made effective use of the window of opportunity for restructuring which the special safeguard provisions have provided, despite investments being made in electricity co-generation and ethanol production.</p><p>Meanwhile, Tanzania, despite being a net importer (with production of 300,000 tonnes and consumption at 330,000 tonnes), is expanding its sugar sales to regional markets. Tanzanian sugar is currently exported to Kenya, Uganda, Burundi, the DRC and southern Sudan. With Tanzanian domestic sugar production increasing and expected to fully meet domestic consumption needs in the next couple of seasons, the Tanzanian Sugar Board is already putting in place market development strategies targeting â€˜new customers and new marketsâ€™ in the region.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<i>Daily Nation</i>, â€˜Clock ticking for sugar industryâ€™, 31 December 2010<br/>

<a href="http://www.nation.co.ke/business/news/Clock%20ticking%20for%20sugar%20industry%20/-/1006/1081730/-/faj4qn/-/" target="_self">http://www.nation.co.ke/business/news/Clock%20ticking%20for%20sugar%20in...</a><br/>
<i>Tanzania Daily News</i>, â€˜Sugar Board expands regional marketsâ€™, 26 December 2010<br/>
<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/201012280456.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/201012280456.html</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Given political divisions in Kenya and impending elections, the dismantling of sugar sector protection, in line with Kenyaâ€™s COMESA commitments, could prove highly problematic. The political dimension to sugar sector policy in Kenya highlights the sensitivity of living up to general regional trade policy commitments when it comes to sensitive agricultural products. Many individual countries have individual sensitive products for which they would like to see special dispensations made under regional trade integration arrangements. While efforts are under way to establish transparent regional rules to regulate these special dispensations, political sensitivities at national level may mean that when decision time is reached, national concerns take precedence over regional policy commitments. Resolving this dilemma lies at the heart of efforts to promote regional integration in the food and agricultural sector, as a means of enhancing regional food security in the face of the challenge of climate change and increasingly volatile food prices.</p>
		</div>
		
